The treaty, negotiated and adopted in Oslo, Norway, in September, bans the use, production, stockpiling and transfer of antipersonnel landmines. About 12 countries have  destroyed their entire stocks of land mines. The document was a "framework of a blueprint" and it "sets out directions," he said. Those who have signed then have four years to destroy their stockpiles of landmines and 10 years to clear minefields. The United States has refused to sign or ratify the treaty, maintaining such weapons are needed on the Korean peninsula to deter North Korea from invading South Korea. Half of Britain's one million landmines have already been destroyed.     UNITED NATIONS  _ World leaders and international organizations on Thursday praised the quick ratification of a treaty aimed at eliminating antipersonnel land mines which now goes into effect in six months. The treaty was signed by more than 120 countries at a landmark meeting in Ottawa last December. They killed or maimed more than 1,000 people in Angola.   BEIRUT, November 14   Canadian Foreign Minister Lloyd Axworthy today failed to take Lebanon into signing the Convention to Ban AntiPersonnel Mines during meetings with Lebanese leaders.